The past year has been a stressful one! We probably aren’t the only ones noticing that extra stress, our kids are too. 

It's an excellent time to remind ourselves of positive emotional regulation strategies. 

Some of those strategies can be: 

✔️ Using a sensory bin, bottle or bag ✔️ Taking a break to go get a drink
✔️ Deep breathing techniques 
✔️ Taking a walk 
✔️ Heavy work (proprioception) activities 
✔️ Coloring or drawing 
✔️ Reading 

Addressing emotions and providing emotional regulation tools will be so important in the coming year as we all hopefully get back to a “normal” school year. 

That is why I have teamed up with some other authors, therapists, and educators and created an incredible resource just for YOU!

The Creating Connections Toolkit includes high-quality, “quick win” resources that will give you what you need right now to help your child or student learn to recognize and manage their emotions.

This is the second year (and my first!!) of the sale, so if you purchased last year, this year’s products are completely BRAND NEW! There are no duplicates of any of the products from last year. 

This digital download toolkit includes resources to help with emotional regulation, sensory processing, and mindfulness and affirmations for all ages. 

Addressing each of these areas can help build stronger connections between you and your students. 

For 5 days, we’ve massively discounted the Creating Connections Toolkit by 93%. That means between now and Tuesday, July 13, you can get $270 worth of products for just $19! 

USE THE LINK IN MY BIO TO BUY YOURS NOW 

P.S. Because we have bundled these tools together to offer you 93% off, it is only available for a very short time. You can pick up your digital toolkit from July 8-13, 2021 only. Grab it now using the link in my bio.

node.text:
Creating an obstacle course is much easier than you think. I grabbed a few outdoor toys like our toddler slide and basketball hoop and sidewalk chalk; and other supplies like pit balls, a cardboard box and painter’s tape. Have multiple ages kids? Get your older kids to help create one for their younger sibling! This was a total hit with everyone! To help you create your own, I created a post with 20 more fun and easy to create backyard obstacle courses for kids.  From a spy training course to a pool noodle course to a water park course. See the full list using the link in my profile. 
AGE: 2 years + 
MESS Level: low 
DIFFICULTY TO CREATE: low
SKILLS DEVELOPED:  gross motor skills, hand-eye coordination, imaginative play, creativity.

I partnered with @michaelsstores #ad #makeitwithmichaels to create these 3 fun sensory bottle crafts!

HOW TO MAKE

1. Take your sensory bottle and add animals and glitter.

2. Fill 2/3 of the sensory bottle with warm water.

3. Fill the rest of the sensory bottle with clear glue.

4. Close tightly and shake. You will get some bubbles. These will go away shortly.

5. Decorate the outside of the sensory bottle with the stickers.

6. Seal the sensory bottle with duct tape.

7. Shake and enjoy!

WHAT YOU'LL NEED TO MAKE THE DINOSAUR SENSORY BOTTLE

- Warm water

- Sensory bottle

https://www.michaels.com/sensory-bottle-by-artminds/10551888.html

- Green glitter

https://www.michaels.com/extra-fine-glitter-stacker-artminds/10226109.html

-Dinosaur stickers

https://www.michaels.com/safari-ltd-good-luck-minis-dino-fun-pack/10382708.html

This activity mama needs a vacation. How about you? If you are lucky enough to be heading to a vacation rental (or cottage for my Canadian 🇨🇦 followers) with little kids this summer? The best part about a vacation home is hanging out with family, water sports, s’mores over a campfire and just enjoying lakeside life. I don’t always like to bring a whole bunch of toys or “activities” largely because I need a break 😅 and nothing beats nature as a way to keep kids entertained! But we all know with little ones it helps to have a few key things on hand to help keep them safe and entertained so you can sit and enjoy that adult beverage 😉. Check out my list of things to bring with you to your vacation rental to keep your little (and big) kids happy. Every year I add to this list based on our my experiences at the cottage with 3 kids. ☀️SUMMER READING BINGO☀️
#sponsored How awesome would it be if kids were excited to read and learn during the summer? Summer shouldn’t mean a break from learning, especially reading AND especially not following this past year.  With virtual schooling and the lack of extracurricular activities and camps, gaps in our kids learning are present like never before. 
 
So, when I heard @teddygrahams had partnered with @savethechildren to support their 100 Days of Reading to help share activities and tips to keep kids learning and reading in the summer, I was happy to help spread the word. 
 
Getting kids to read during the summer is tough. I feel blessed to have a 7 year old that loves to read. But that isn’t always the case for many kids. If you struggle getting your child to read especially in the summer, try one of these fun and easy Summer Reading Activities for Kids.  And reading can be even more fun when you have @teddygrahams as a snack, with no high fructose corn syrup and 8 grams of whole grain in every serving!
 
1. Journaling: keep a journal in the summer, include drawings or pictures. 
2. Play Summer Reading Bingo: Set a reading time and goal for. Decide on prizes such as a special trip, treat or toy or anything they really want. Start reading and keep reading.  As they read let them cross items in the bingo chart.
3. Cook together and let them read the recipe. 
4. Traveling? Let them write and send post cards to friends and family. 
5. Story Telling Sticks: write out a story on craft sticks and let them arrange them in order and read the story. 
6. Treasure Hunt: hide old or new toys, treats and write out clues they must read to find the items. 
 
Follow @teddygrahams for more tools and tips to keep kids learning and reading all summer. 
 
And follow @savethechildren to find out more about their 100 Days of Reading campaign.
